An icon can help convey a function when put next to text. For example, a printer icon on a button labelled “Print this page”.

When icons are used in the same way everywhere, they can make your product easier to use. Recognisable icons can make scanning a page quicker, as well as making target areas larger to select. They can also help users who have learning disabilities, such as dyslexia.

## When to use icons

### Use recognisable icons
Only use icons that are universally understood and have been proved by user research, to help users understand something more quickly. A large familiar icon can be quicker to understand when scanning a page than reading a text label on it’s own.

